#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:5
msgid "Development workflow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:7
msgid ""
"You already have your own forked copy of the NumPy repository, have "
"configured Git, and have linked the upstream repository as explained in :ref:"
"`linking-to-upstream`. What is described below is a recommended workflow "
"with Git."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:13
msgid "Basic workflow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:15
msgid "In short:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:17
msgid ""
"Start a new *feature branch* for each set of edits that you do. See :ref:"
"`below <making-a-new-feature-branch>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:20
msgid "Hack away! See :ref:`below <editing-workflow>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:22
msgid "When finished:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:24
msgid ""
"*Contributors*: push your feature branch to your own Github repo, and :ref:"
"`create a pull request <asking-for-merging>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:27
msgid ""
"*Core developers*: If you want to push changes without further review, see "
"the notes :ref:`below <pushing-to-main>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:30
msgid ""
"This way of working helps to keep work well organized and the history as "
"clear as possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:36
msgid "Making a new feature branch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:38
msgid "First, fetch new commits from the ``upstream`` repository:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:42
#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:300
msgid "git fetch upstream"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:44
msgid ""
"Then, create a new branch based on the main branch of the upstream "
"repository::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:47
msgid "git checkout -b my-new-feature upstream/main"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:53
msgid "The editing workflow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:56
msgid "Overview"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:60
msgid ""
"# hack hack\n"
"git status # Optional\n"
"git diff # Optional\n"
"git add modified_file\n"
"git commit\n"
"# push the branch to your own Github repo\n"
"git push origin my-new-feature"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:69
msgid "In more detail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:71
msgid ""
"Make some changes. When you feel that you've made a complete, working set of "
"related changes, move on to the next steps."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:74
msgid ""
"Optional: Check which files have changed with ``git status``. You'll see a "
"listing like this one::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:77
msgid ""
"# On branch my-new-feature\n"
"# Changed but not updated:\n"
"#   (use \"git add <file>...\" to update what will be committed)\n"
"#   (use \"git checkout -- <file>...\" to discard changes in working "
"directory)\n"
"#\n"
"#  modified:   README\n"
"#\n"
"# Untracked files:\n"
"#   (use \"git add <file>...\" to include in what will be committed)\n"
"#\n"
"#  INSTALL\n"
"no changes added to commit (use \"git add\" and/or \"git commit -a\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:90
msgid ""
"Optional: Compare the changes with the previous version using with ``git "
"diff``. This brings up a simple text browser interface that highlights the "
"difference between your files and the previous version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:94
msgid ""
"Add any relevant modified or new files using  ``git add modified_file``. "
"This puts the files into a staging area, which is a queue of files that will "
"be added to your next commit. Only add files that have related, complete "
"changes. Leave files with unfinished changes for later commits."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:100
msgid ""
"To commit the staged files into the local copy of your repo, do ``git "
"commit``. At this point, a text editor will open up to allow you to write a "
"commit message. Read the :ref:`commit message section<writing-the-commit-"
"message>` to be sure that you are writing a properly formatted and "
"sufficiently detailed commit message. After saving your message and closing "
"the editor, your commit will be saved. For trivial commits, a short commit "
"message can be passed in through the command line using the ``-m`` flag. For "
"example, ``git commit -am \"ENH: Some message\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:109
msgid ""
"In some cases, you will see this form of the commit command: ``git commit -"
"a``. The extra ``-a`` flag automatically commits all modified files and "
"removes all deleted files. This can save you some typing of numerous ``git "
"add`` commands; however, it can add unwanted changes to a commit if you're "
"not careful."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:115
msgid "Push the changes to your fork on GitHub::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:117
msgid "git push origin my-new-feature"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:121
msgid ""
"Assuming you have followed the instructions in these pages, git will create "
"a default link to your GitHb repo called ``origin``.  You can ensure that "
"the link to origin is permanently set by using the ``--set-upstream`` "
"option::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:126
msgid "git push --set-upstream origin my-new-feature"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:128
msgid ""
"From now on, ``git`` will know that ``my-new-feature`` is related to the "
"``my-new-feature`` branch in your own GitHub repo. Subsequent push calls are "
"then simplified to the following::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:132
msgid "git push"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:134
msgid "You have to use ``--set-upstream`` for each new branch that you create."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:137
msgid ""
"It may be the case that while you were working on your edits, new commits "
"have been added to ``upstream`` that affect your work. In this case, follow "
"the :ref:`rebasing-on-main` section of this document to apply those changes "
"to your branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:145
msgid "Writing the commit message"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:147
msgid ""
"Commit messages should be clear and follow a few basic rules.  Example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:149
msgid ""
"ENH: add functionality X to numpy.<submodule>.\n"
"\n"
"The first line of the commit message starts with a capitalized acronym\n"
"(options listed below) indicating what type of commit this is.  Then a "
"blank\n"
"line, then more text if needed.  Lines shouldn't be longer than 72\n"
"characters.  If the commit is related to a ticket, indicate that with\n"
"\"See #3456\", \"See ticket 3456\", \"Closes #3456\" or similar."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:157
msgid ""
"Describing the motivation for a change, the nature of a bug for bug fixes or "
"some details on what an enhancement does are also good to include in a "
"commit message.  Messages should be understandable without looking at the "
"code changes.  A commit message like ``MAINT: fixed another one`` is an "
"example of what not to do; the reader has to go look for context elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:163
msgid "Standard acronyms to start the commit message with are::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:165
msgid ""
"API: an (incompatible) API change\n"
"BENCH: changes to the benchmark suite\n"
"BLD: change related to building numpy\n"
"BUG: bug fix\n"
"CI: continuous integration\n"
"DEP: deprecate something, or remove a deprecated object\n"
"DEV: development tool or utility\n"
"DOC: documentation\n"
"ENH: enhancement\n"
"MAINT: maintenance commit (refactoring, typos, etc.)\n"
"MNT: alias for MAINT\n"
"NEP: NumPy enhancement proposals\n"
"REL: related to releasing numpy\n"
"REV: revert an earlier commit\n"
"STY: style fix (whitespace, PEP8)\n"
"TST: addition or modification of tests\n"
"TYP: static typing\n"
"WIP: work in progress, do not merge"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:185
msgid "Commands to skip continuous integration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:187
msgid ""
"By default a lot of continuous integration (CI) jobs are run for every PR, "
"from running the test suite on different operating systems and hardware "
"platforms to building the docs. In some cases you already know that CI isn't "
"needed (or not all of it), for example if you work on CI config files, text "
"in the README, or other files that aren't involved in regular build, test or "
"docs sequences. In such cases you may explicitly skip CI by including one or "
"more of these fragments in each commit message of a PR:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:195
msgid "``[skip ci]``: skip all CI"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:197
msgid ""
"Only recommended if you are still not ready for the checks to run on your PR "
"(for example, if this is only a draft.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:200
msgid "``[skip actions]``: skip GitHub Actions jobs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:202
msgid ""
"`GitHub Actions <https://docs.github.com/actions>`__ is where most of the CI "
"checks are run, including the linter, benchmarking, running basic tests for "
"most architectures and OSs, and several compiler and CPU optimization "
"settings. `See the configuration files for these checks. <https://github.com/"
"numpy/numpy/tree/main/.github/workflows>`__"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:208
msgid "``[skip circle]``: skip CircleCI jobs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:210
msgid ""
"`CircleCI <https://circleci.com/>`__ is where we build the documentation and "
"store the generated artifact for preview in each PR. This check will also "
"run all the docstrings examples and verify their results. If you don't make "
"documentation changes, but you make changes to a function's API, for "
"example, you may need to run these tests to verify that the doctests are "
"still valid. `See the configuration file for these checks. <https://github."
"com/numpy/numpy/blob/main/.circleci/config.yml>`__"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:217
msgid "``[skip cirrus]``: skip Cirrus jobs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:219
msgid ""
"`CirrusCI <https://cirrus-ci.org/>`__ mostly triggers Linux aarch64 and "
"MacOS Arm64 wheels uploads. `See the configuration file for these checks. "
"<https://github.com/numpy/numpy/blob/main/.cirrus.star>`__"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:224
msgid "Test building wheels"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:226
msgid ""
"Numpy currently uses `cibuildwheel <https://cibuildwheel.readthedocs.io/en/"
"stable/>`_ in order to build wheels through continuous integration services. "
"To save resources, the cibuildwheel wheel builders are not run by default on "
"every single PR or commit to main."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:230
msgid ""
"If you would like to test that your pull request do not break the wheel "
"builders, you can do so by appending ``[wheel build]`` to the first line of "
"the commit message of the newest commit in your PR. Please only do so for "
"build-related PRs, because running all wheel builds is slow and expensive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:235
msgid ""
"The wheels built via github actions (including 64-bit Linux, x86-64 macOS, "
"and 32/64-bit Windows) will be uploaded as artifacts in zip files. You can "
"access them from the Summary page of the \"Wheel builder\" action. The "
"aarch64 Linux and arm64 macOS wheels built via Cirrus CI are not available "
"as artifacts. Additionally, the wheels will be uploaded to https://anaconda."
"org/scientific-python-nightly-wheels/ on the following conditions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:242
msgid "by a weekly cron job or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:243
msgid ""
"if the GitHub Actions or Cirrus build has been manually triggered, which "
"requires appropriate permissions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:246
msgid ""
"The wheels will be uploaded to https://anaconda.org/multibuild-wheels-"
"staging/ if the build was triggered by a tag to the repo that begins with "
"``v``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:253
msgid "Get the mailing list's opinion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:255
msgid ""
"If you plan a new feature or API change, it's wisest to first email the "
"NumPy `mailing list <https://mail.python.org/mailman/listinfo/numpy-"
"discussion>`_ asking for comment. If you haven't heard back in a week, it's "
"OK to ping the list again."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:264
msgid "Asking for your changes to be merged with the main repo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:266
msgid ""
"When you feel your work is finished, you can create a pull request (PR). If "
"your changes involve modifications to the API or addition/modification of a "
"function, add a release note to the ``doc/release/upcoming_changes/`` "
"directory, following the instructions and format in the ``doc/release/"
"upcoming_changes/README.rst`` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:272
msgid ""
"Use the same prefix convention for your pull request title as for commit "
"messages (e.g., ``BUG:``, ``ENH:``, ``DOC:``). This enables automated "
"labeling of your PR."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:280
msgid "Getting your PR reviewed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:282
msgid ""
"We review pull requests as soon as we can, typically within a week. If you "
"get no review comments within two weeks, feel free to ask for feedback by "
"adding a comment on your PR (this will notify maintainers)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:286
msgid ""
"If your PR is large or complicated, asking for input on the numpy-discussion "
"mailing list may also be useful."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:293
msgid "Rebasing on main"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:295
msgid ""
"This updates your feature branch with changes from the upstream NumPy GitHub "
"repo. If you do not absolutely need to do this, try to avoid doing it, "
"except perhaps when you are finished. The first step will be to update the "
"remote repository with new commits from upstream::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:302
msgid "Next, you need to update the feature branch::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:304
msgid ""
"# go to the feature branch\n"
"git checkout my-new-feature\n"
"# make a backup in case you mess up\n"
"git branch tmp my-new-feature\n"
"# rebase on upstream main branch\n"
"git rebase upstream/main"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:311
msgid ""
"If you have made changes to files that have changed also upstream, this may "
"generate merge conflicts that you need to resolve. See :ref:"
"`below<recovering-from-mess-up>` for help in this case."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:315
msgid "Finally, remove the backup branch upon a successful rebase::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:317
msgid "git branch -D tmp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:322
msgid ""
"Rebasing on main is preferred over merging upstream back to your branch. "
"Using ``git merge`` and ``git pull`` is discouraged when working on feature "
"branches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:329
msgid "Recovering from mess-ups"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:331
msgid ""
"Sometimes, you mess up merges or rebases. Luckily, in Git it is relatively "
"straightforward to recover from such mistakes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:334
msgid "If you mess up during a rebase::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:336
msgid "git rebase --abort"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:338
msgid "If you notice you messed up after the rebase::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:340
msgid ""
"# reset branch back to the saved point\n"
"git reset --hard tmp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:343
msgid "If you forgot to make a backup branch::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:345
msgid ""
"# look at the reflog of the branch\n"
"git reflog show my-feature-branch\n"
"\n"
"8630830 my-feature-branch@{0}: commit: BUG: io: close file handles "
"immediately\n"
"278dd2a my-feature-branch@{1}: rebase finished: refs/heads/my-feature-branch "
"onto 11ee694744f2552d\n"
"26aa21a my-feature-branch@{2}: commit: BUG: lib: make seek_gzip_factory not "
"leak gzip obj\n"
"...\n"
"\n"
"# reset the branch to where it was before the botched rebase\n"
"git reset --hard my-feature-branch@{2}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:356
msgid ""
"If you didn't actually mess up but there are merge conflicts, you need to "
"resolve those."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:361
msgid "Additional things you might want to do"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:366
msgid "Rewriting commit history"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:370
msgid "Do this only for your own feature branches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:372
msgid ""
"There's an embarrassing typo in a commit you made? Or perhaps you made "
"several false starts you would like the posterity not to see."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:375
msgid "This can be done via *interactive rebasing*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:377
msgid "Suppose that the commit history looks like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:379
msgid ""
"git log --oneline\n"
"eadc391 Fix some remaining bugs\n"
"a815645 Modify it so that it works\n"
"2dec1ac Fix a few bugs + disable\n"
"13d7934 First implementation\n"
"6ad92e5 * masked is now an instance of a new object, MaskedConstant\n"
"29001ed Add pre-nep for a couple of structured_array_extensions.\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:388
msgid ""
"and ``6ad92e5`` is the last commit in the ``main`` branch. Suppose we want "
"to make the following changes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:391
msgid "Rewrite the commit message for ``13d7934`` to something more sensible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:392
msgid ""
"Combine the commits ``2dec1ac``, ``a815645``, ``eadc391`` into a single one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:394
msgid "We do as follows::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:396
msgid ""
"# make a backup of the current state\n"
"git branch tmp HEAD\n"
"# interactive rebase\n"
"git rebase -i 6ad92e5"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:401
msgid "This will open an editor with the following text in it::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:403
msgid ""
"pick 13d7934 First implementation\n"
"pick 2dec1ac Fix a few bugs + disable\n"
"pick a815645 Modify it so that it works\n"
"pick eadc391 Fix some remaining bugs\n"
"\n"
"# Rebase 6ad92e5..eadc391 onto 6ad92e5\n"
"#\n"
"# Commands:\n"
"#  p, pick = use commit\n"
"#  r, reword = use commit, but edit the commit message\n"
"#  e, edit = use commit, but stop for amending\n"
"#  s, squash = use commit, but meld into previous commit\n"
"#  f, fixup = like \"squash\", but discard this commit's log message\n"
"#\n"
"# If you remove a line here THAT COMMIT WILL BE LOST.\n"
"# However, if you remove everything, the rebase will be aborted.\n"
"#"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:421
msgid "To achieve what we want, we will make the following changes to it::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:423
msgid ""
"r 13d7934 First implementation\n"
"pick 2dec1ac Fix a few bugs + disable\n"
"f a815645 Modify it so that it works\n"
"f eadc391 Fix some remaining bugs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:428
msgid ""
"This means that (i) we want to edit the commit message for ``13d7934``, and "
"(ii) collapse the last three commits into one. Now we save and quit the "
"editor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:432
msgid ""
"Git will then immediately bring up an editor for editing the commit message. "
"After revising it, we get the output::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:435
msgid ""
"[detached HEAD 721fc64] FOO: First implementation\n"
" 2 files changed, 199 insertions(+), 66 deletions(-)\n"
"[detached HEAD 0f22701] Fix a few bugs + disable\n"
" 1 files changed, 79 insertions(+), 61 deletions(-)\n"
"Successfully rebased and updated refs/heads/my-feature-branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:441
msgid "and the history looks now like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:443
msgid ""
"0f22701 Fix a few bugs + disable\n"
"721fc64 ENH: Sophisticated feature\n"
"6ad92e5 * masked is now an instance of a new object, MaskedConstant"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:447
msgid ""
"If it went wrong, recovery is again possible as explained :ref:`above "
"<recovering-from-mess-up>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:451
msgid "Deleting a branch on GitHub"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:455
msgid ""
"git checkout main\n"
"# delete branch locally\n"
"git branch -D my-unwanted-branch\n"
"# delete branch on github\n"
"git push origin --delete my-unwanted-branch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:461
msgid ""
"See also: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2003505/how-do-i-delete-a-git-"
"branch-locally-and-remotely"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:466
msgid "Several people sharing a single repository"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:468
msgid ""
"If you want to work on some stuff with other people, where you are all "
"committing into the same repository, or even the same branch, then just "
"share it via GitHub."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:472
msgid "First fork NumPy into your account, as from :ref:`forking`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:474
msgid ""
"Then, go to your forked repository github page, say ``https://github.com/"
"your-user-name/numpy``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:477
msgid ""
"Click on the 'Admin' button, and add anyone else to the repo as a "
"collaborator:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:482
msgid "Now all those people can do::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:484
msgid "git clone git@github.com:your-user-name/numpy.git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:486
msgid ""
"Remember that links starting with ``git@`` use the ssh protocol and are read-"
"write; links starting with ``git://`` are read-only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:489
msgid ""
"Your collaborators can then commit directly into that repo with the usual::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:492
msgid ""
"git commit -am 'ENH - much better code'\n"
"git push origin my-feature-branch # pushes directly into your repo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:497
msgid "Checkout changes from an existing pull request"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:499
msgid ""
"If you want to test the changes in a pull request or continue the work in a "
"new pull request, the commits are to be cloned into a local branch in your "
"forked repository"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:503
msgid ""
"First ensure your upstream points to the main repo, as from :ref:`linking-to-"
"upstream`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:505
msgid ""
"Then, fetch the changes and create a local branch. Assuming ``$ID`` is the "
"pull request number and ``$BRANCHNAME`` is the name of the *new local* "
"branch you wish to create::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:508
msgid "git fetch upstream pull/$ID/head:$BRANCHNAME"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:510
msgid "Checkout the newly created branch::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:512
msgid "git checkout $BRANCHNAME"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:514
msgid "You now have the changes in the pull request."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:518
msgid "Exploring your repository"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:520
msgid ""
"To see a graphical representation of the repository branches and commits::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:523
msgid "gitk --all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:525
msgid "To see a linear list of commits for this branch::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:527
msgid "git log"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:531
msgid "Backporting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:533
msgid ""
"Backporting is the process of copying new feature/fixes committed in NumPy's "
"``main`` branch back to stable release branches. To do this you make a "
"branch off the branch you are backporting to, cherry pick the commits you "
"want from ``numpy/main``, and then submit a pull request for the branch "
"containing the backport."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:539
msgid ""
"First, you need to make the branch you will work on. This needs to be based "
"on the older version of NumPy (not main)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:542
msgid ""
"# Make a new branch based on numpy/maintenance/1.8.x,\n"
"# backport-3324 is our new name for the branch.\n"
"git checkout -b backport-3324 upstream/maintenance/1.8.x"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:546
msgid ""
"Now you need to apply the changes from main to this branch using ``git "
"cherry-pick``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:549
msgid ""
"# Update remote\n"
"git fetch upstream\n"
"# Check the commit log for commits to cherry pick\n"
"git log upstream/main\n"
"# This pull request included commits aa7a047 to c098283 (inclusive)\n"
"# so you use the .. syntax (for a range of commits), the ^ makes the\n"
"# range inclusive.\n"
"git cherry-pick aa7a047^..c098283\n"
"...\n"
"# Fix any conflicts, then if needed:\n"
"git cherry-pick --continue"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:561
msgid ""
"You might run into some conflicts cherry picking here. These are resolved "
"the same way as merge/rebase conflicts. Except here you can use ``git "
"blame`` to see the difference between main and the backported branch to make "
"sure nothing gets screwed up."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:566
msgid "Push the new branch to your Github repository::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:568
msgid "git push -u origin backport-3324"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:570
msgid ""
"Finally make a pull request using Github. Make sure it is against the "
"maintenance branch and not main, Github will usually suggest you make the "
"pull request against main."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:577
msgid "Pushing changes to the main repo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:579
msgid "*Requires commit rights to the main NumPy repo.*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:581
msgid ""
"When you have a set of \"ready\" changes in a feature branch ready for "
"NumPy's ``main`` or ``maintenance`` branches, you can push them to "
"``upstream`` as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:585
msgid "First, merge or rebase on the target branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:587
msgid "Only a few, unrelated commits then prefer rebasing::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:589
msgid ""
"git fetch upstream\n"
"git rebase upstream/main"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:592
msgid "See :ref:`rebasing-on-main`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:594
msgid "If all of the commits are related, create a merge commit::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:596
msgid ""
"git fetch upstream\n"
"git merge --no-ff upstream/main"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:599
msgid "Check that what you are going to push looks sensible::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:601
msgid ""
"git log -p upstream/main..\n"
"git log --oneline --graph"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:604
msgid "Push to upstream::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:606
msgid "git push upstream my-feature-branch:main"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/development_workflow.rst:610
msgid ""
"It's usually a good idea to use the ``-n`` flag to ``git push`` to check "
"first that you're about to push the changes you want to the place you want."
msgstr ""
